The paper discusses information measures and entropy quantification, which are commonly studied in the field of information theory (cs.IT). The study also takes into account microphysical codependence, which suggests a focus on complex systems and statistical physics (cs.SI). The use of redundancy and synergy to evaluate macroscale variables also suggests a focus on machine learning and data analysis (cs.MA). The study also involves analyzing interactions among microstates, which is a common theme in dynamical systems (cs.DS). Finally, the study emphasizes the added value of nonlinear statistical physics to information theory, which suggests a focus on machine learning and statistical methods (cs.LG).
